Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["12. References", "Section",ExpressionUUID->"fadc0aef-c804-1f4e-846f-e709127e757d"],

Cell["\<\
[1] Avraham, R. and Gilo, D. (2025). Insurance Collusion and Imperfect \
Competition when Insurers Increase Risk. Working Paper, Tel Aviv University.

[2] Arrow, K.J. (1965). Aspects of the Theory of Risk-Bearing. Yrjo Jahnsson \
Lectures.

[3] Pratt, J.W. (1964). Risk Aversion in the Small and in the Large. \
Econometrica, 32(1-2), 122-136.

[4] Mossin, J. (1968). Aspects of Rational Insurance Purchasing. Journal of \
Political Economy, 76(4), 553-568.

[5] Friend, I. and Blume, M.E. (1975). The Demand for Risky Assets. American \
Economic Review, 65(5), 900-922. [Empirical CRRA estimates gamma = 2-5]\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"059928f9-c370-e243-a647-8a1a354e2513"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Appendix: Plain-English Proof \[LongDash] Lemma 1(i) for CRRA Utility", \
"Section",ExpressionUUID->"1722c757-5b9f-6947-b345-57fc523d5402"],

Cell["\<\
This appendix presents a self-contained, step-by-step mathematical proof with \
no code. All equation numbers refer to Avraham and Gilo (2025).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"f44470b7-97bc-7549-aee5-f2a5facf9e0e"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A.1  Setup and Notation", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"a04c20dd-331c-ca41-98a4-0621b0f1228a"],

Cell["\<\
A risk-averse consumer with wealth W > 0 faces harm H > 0 (with W > H) \
occurring with probability P \[Element] (0,1). Insurance coverage \[Alpha] \
\[Element] [0,1] costs premium \[Alpha]qPH, where q \[GreaterEqual] 1 is the \
loading factor.

Wealth in each state:
  No accident:  W1 = W - \[Alpha]qPH
  Accident:     W2 = W - H + \[Alpha]H(1 - qP)

We specialize to CRRA utility:  U(A) = A^(1-\[Gamma]) / (1-\[Gamma]),  \
\[Gamma] > 0

Arrow-Pratt absolute risk aversion:  Ra(A) = \[Gamma]/A    (Decreasing \
Absolute Risk Aversion)\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"1bcae778-9ffd-a947-92a2-03a2a1b252f3"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A.2  The First-Order Condition (FOC)", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"29fbdcff-f5b8-8c4c-8478-40ae35a2a653"],

Cell["\<\
The consumer maximizes EU = (1-P)U(W1) + PU(W2). The FOC (Equation 1) is:

    -(1-P)qU'(W1) + (1-qP)U'(W2) = 0          ...(FOC)

This gives:   U'(W2)/U'(W1) = (1-P)q / (1-qP)          ...(FOC')

For CRRA, U'(A) = A^(-\[Gamma]), so:

    (W2/W1)^\[Gamma] = (1-P)q / (1-qP)          ...(FOC-CRRA)\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"93817cbf-5ed5-864e-a9c7-87e4fa58a247"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A.3  Optimal Coverage at P \[Rule] 0", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"58295f74-66a1-ab4d-90ee-3d81161b792f"],

Cell["\<\
As P \[Rule] 0, W1 \[Rule] W and W2 \[Rule] W - H(1-\[Alpha]). The FOC-CRRA \
becomes:

    (W - H(1-\[Alpha]))^(-\[Gamma]) = q W^(-\[Gamma])

Rearranging:
    W - H(1-\[Alpha]) = W q^(-1/\[Gamma])          ...(1)

Solving for \[Alpha]:
    H(1-\[Alpha]) = W(1 - q^(-1/\[Gamma]))

    \[Alpha]0(\[Gamma]) = 1 - (W/H)(1 - q^(-1/\[Gamma]))          ...(2)

This is the key result: optimal coverage at P \[Rule] 0 depends on \[Gamma]. \
More risk-averse consumers (higher \[Gamma]) purchase more coverage.

For \[Alpha]0 > 0 we need H > W(1 - q^(-1/\[Gamma])).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"844a1989-25d6-a44d-9a1f-8aaade496e40"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A.4  The Derivative of Coverage (Equation 17)", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"a3a63134-941e-4f4a-9146-1205ae3552a7"],

Cell["\<\
From the paper's Appendix, Equation (17):

    d(\[Alpha]*)/dP = Numerator / Denominator

where:
    Numerator  = (1-P)\[Alpha]qH[Ra(W1) - Ra(W2)] + (q-1)/(1-qP)
    Denominator = -(1-P)H[qP Ra(W1) + (1-qP) Ra(W2)]

The denominator is always NEGATIVE (Ra > 0, H > 0, P \[Element] (0,1)).

Therefore:
  If Numerator < 0, then d(\[Alpha]*)/dP > 0 (coverage increases with risk)
  If Numerator > 0, then d(\[Alpha]*)/dP < 0 (coverage decreases with risk)\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"6f574178-1a06-bc43-b669-25d76a3b0ff9"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A.5  The Numerator at P \[Rule] 0 (Equation 18)", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"a028353d-3eee-2f46-9aca-6315e9ad8b7f"],

Cell["\<\
As P \[Rule] 0, the numerator converges to:

    N0 = \[Alpha]0 q H [Ra(W) - Ra(W - H(1-\[Alpha]0))] + (q-1)          \
...(18)

For CRRA, Ra(A) = \[Gamma]/A:

    N0 = \[Alpha]0 q H \[Gamma] [1/W - 1/(W - H(1-\[Alpha]0))] + (q-1)

The bracketed term = -H(1-\[Alpha]0) / [W(W-H(1-\[Alpha]0))] < 0

So the first term is negative, while (q-1) > 0 for q > 1.
Lemma 1(i) requires N0 < 0: the risk-aversion effect must dominate.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"56900656-f92f-2944-83fb-fa760ea83b6d"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A.6  The Self-Consistency Problem (KEY INSIGHT)", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"79ae8867-89d5-5042-8c89-44be960e98eb"],

Cell["\<\
Setting N0 = 0 gives a naive critical gamma formula:

    \[Gamma]crit = (q-1) W (W-H(1-\[Alpha]0)) / (\[Alpha]0 q H\[ThinSpace]^2 \
(1-\[Alpha]0))          ...(19')

BUT \[Alpha]0 itself depends on \[Gamma] through the FOC (Equation 2):

    \[Alpha]0(\[Gamma]) = 1 - (W/H)(1 - q^(-1/\[Gamma]))

So the condition for Lemma 1(i) is the IMPLICIT inequality:

    \[Gamma] > \[Gamma]crit(\[Gamma])

where \[Gamma]crit depends on \[Gamma] through \[Alpha]0(\[Gamma]). This \
CANNOT be checked by holding \[Alpha] fixed at some value. The naive approach \
(which GPT-5 and the initial notebook used) gives incorrect results.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"ad016935-c227-1e41-8ad3-50f290278bdd"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A.7  Asymptotic Analysis: \[Gamma] \[Rule] \[Infinity]", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"75e4150b-57ab-f543-bfc9-ee764d424176"],

Cell["\<\
As \[Gamma] \[Rule] \[Infinity]:

  (1) q^(-1/\[Gamma]) \[Rule] 1, so \[Alpha]0 \[Rule] 1 (nearly full \
coverage)
  (2) W2 = W - H(1-\[Alpha]0) \[Rule] W (wealth gap vanishes)

Using Taylor expansion q^(-1/\[Gamma]) \[TildeTilde] 1 - ln(q)/\[Gamma]:

    H(1-\[Alpha]0) \[TildeTilde] W ln(q)/\[Gamma]

The product \[Gamma] [1/W - 1/W2] has form \[Infinity] \[Times] 0. Resolving:

    \[Gamma] [1/W - 1/(W - W ln(q)/\[Gamma])] \[Rule] -ln(q)/W

Therefore N0 converges to:

    N0 \[Rule] 1 q H (-ln(q)/W) + (q-1) = (q-1) - qH ln(q)/W

For W=100, H=40, q=1.3:
    N0 \[Rule] 0.3 - 1.3 \[Times] 40 \[Times] 0.2624 / 100 = 0.3 - 0.136 = \
+0.164 > 0

The limit is POSITIVE. Since N0 is continuous and positive for all \[Gamma], \
it never crosses zero. Lemma 1(i) is NEVER satisfied for CRRA utility with \
these parameters.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"683e0162-c1b7-eb40-9e24-8d770bba0006"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A.8  Necessary Condition on Parameters", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"6fcc03da-d7fc-6b4b-a03c-bde0dff2726e"],

Cell["\<\
For Lemma 1(i) to hold with CRRA, the asymptotic limit must be non-positive:

    (q-1) - qH ln(q)/W \[LessEqual] 0

Solving:    H/W \[GreaterEqual] (q-1) / (q ln(q))

For q = 1.3:  H/W \[GreaterEqual] 0.880      (harm must be 88% of wealth)
For q = 1.1:  H/W \[GreaterEqual] 0.954
For q = 1.5:  H/W \[GreaterEqual] 0.822

The harm must represent at least ~88% of wealth (for q=1.3) for CRRA utility \
to produce single-peaked demand. This corresponds to catastrophic, \
near-total-loss events.\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"a8795339-e659-4446-9f8f-112df5a24f93"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A.9  Economic Intuition", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"6b68faf4-bd2b-a642-90d4-53559422b786"],

Cell["\<\
Why does CRRA utility fail to satisfy Lemma 1(i) for typical parameters?

The condition requires Ra(A) to decrease 'sufficiently fast' with wealth. For \
CRRA, Ra(A) = \[Gamma]/A. As \[Gamma] increases:

  (a) Risk aversion increases everywhere
      \[Rule] pushes Ra(W1)-Ra(W2) more negative (favors Lemma 1(i))

  (b) BUT optimal coverage \[Alpha]0 also increases toward 1
      \[Rule] the wealth gap W1-W2 shrinks
      \[Rule] Ra(W1) and Ra(W2) become nearly equal (works AGAINST Lemma 1(i))

These two effects approximately CANCEL for CRRA utility, leaving the loading \
term (q-1) > 0 as the dominant contribution to N0.

Utility functions where Lemma 1(i) DOES hold need Ra(A) to decrease FASTER \
than 1/A. Candidates include HARA utility with Ra(A) = 1/(a+bA), or utility \
functions with Decreasing Relative Risk Aversion (DRRA).\
\>", "Text",ExpressionUUID->"e3220b6c-7a2e-524e-89d9-300af4b40046"]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["A.10  Numerical Verification", "Subsection",ExpressionUUID->"1c0b3b05-3ca0-7f41-9ec2-a93e985e14bf"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["\<\
(* Self-consistent N0 computation *)
Print[\"=== Self-Consistent N0 Verification (W=100, H=40, q=1.3) ===\"];
Print[\"gamma | alpha0(gamma) | N0        | Lemma 1(i)?\"];
Do[
  Module[{a0, w2val, n0val},
    a0 = N[1 - (100/40)*(1 - 1.3^(-1/g))];
    If[a0 <= 0,
      Print[g, \" | no coverage  | N/A      | N/A\"],
      w2val = 100 - 40*(1 - a0);
      n0val = a0*1.3*40*g*(1/100.0 - 1/w2val) + 0.3;
      Print[g, \" | \", Round[a0, 0.001], \" | \", Round[n0val, 0.0001], \" | \
\",
        If[n0val < 0, \"YES\", \"No (positive)\"]]
    ]
  ],
  {g, {0.5, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 10, 20, 50, 100, 1000}}
];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"Asymptotic limit: N0 -> (q-1) - qH*ln(q)/W = \",
  Round[N[0.3 - 1.3*40*Log[1.3]/100], 0.0001]];
Print[\"\"];
Print[\"CONCLUSION: N0 > 0 for ALL gamma.\"];
Print[\"Lemma 1(i) does NOT hold for CRRA with H/W = 0.4.\"];
Print[\"Required: H/W > \", Round[N[0.3/(1.3*Log[1.3])], 0.001]];\
\>", "Input",
 CellLabel->
  "In[997]:=",ExpressionUUID->"5f5e89ff-104e-0948-8b77-8ee457d1f9b9"],

